Motor Trend - Regression

Joost van Brakel

October 20, 2015

Executive summary

We at Motor Trend are looking to better understand the relationship between miles per gallon and a number design and performance aspects. Our initial focus was on transmitions, however this results provided no viable forecasting models, due to the binary nature of the transmition (Auto / Manual). By researching the other aspects we were able to determinedthat the best way to forecast MPG was by looking at the weight and the horsepower of the car.

Process

For this analysis we used R and a number of key libraries, namely : xtable, GGally, car and ggplot2

data

The data utilized was extracted from the 1974 Motor Trend US magazine, and comprises fuel consumption (MPG) and 10 aspects of automobile design and performance for 32 automobiles (197374 models). The data utilize is part of R and is called mtcars. It was pulled into the dataset variable for analysis and no transformation were performed for this analysis. A legend of the fields is included in appendix 1.

Our first step was to examine the the impact of the transmition type on Miles per Gallon.

As the chart and the statistics above highlight, there is a significant difference between the two transmition types with the with P values below 0.05 and the t test shows that the t value is outside confidence interval.

How different are the MPG stats

However to forecast the MPG of a car using the transmitions as its main factors is not going to provide you much was binary forecast, either Automatic and therefore it will have a mean of 14.7 with a standard deviation of 3.8, or manual transmition of will have a mean of 24.4 with a standard deviation of 6.2. As you can see in the chart below, there is an overlap in MPG between the two groups. To better forecast MPG, we have looked at the broader set of design and performance options. In appendix 2 we include a chart that compares all the different factors. Looking at the correlation with MPG and the factors, we noticed that cylenders, displacements, horsepower and weight have a high correlation(0.75+). We could build a model with all those factors, but that could create the risk of over fitting. To minimize the number of factors we looked at eliminiating factors that had a high correlation between each other. The chart in appendix 3 maps out the relationship between the key factors. It shows that the majority of factors have a high degree of correlation, but weight and horsepower have the lowest correlation.

Taking this correlation into consideration we build 3 reference models. 1. Displacement (highest single factor correlation) 2. Horsepower and Weight 3. Horsepower, Weight and Displacement
Results comparing models
model R Square Adj, R Square
1 Model 1 0.7183 0.7090
2 Model 2 0.8268 0.8148
3 Model 3 0.8268 0.8083

Final results

Comparing the results both model 2 and 3 have acceptable R Squared, and on an R Squared basis both are simular for model 2 and 3, however model 2 has fewer inputs and this results in an improved adjusted r squared. It also has a lower VIF, which we have included in the appendix. Therefore model 2 is the prefered model. We also examined the residuals, which showed no particular patern.

So how to use this model :
Model 2
Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)
(Intercept) 37.2273 1.5988 23.2847 0.0000
wt -3.8778 0.6327 -6.1287 0.0000
hp -0.0318 0.0090 -3.5187 0.0015

To forecast the MPG usage of the car you will have to fill in the following formula :
MPG usage = 37.2 - 3. 88 x Weight - 0.03 x Horsepower

Appendix

1. Legend

Here is the Legend for the fields being utilized in this analysis

  • mpg, Miles/(US) gallon
  • cyl, Number of cylinders
  • disp, Displacement (cu.in.)
  • hp, Gross horsepower
  • drat, Rear axle ratio
  • wt, Weight (lb/1000)
  • qsec, 1/4 mile time
  • vs, V/S
  • am, Transmission (0 = automatic, 1 = manual)
  • gear, Number of forward gears
  • carb, Number of carburetors
